The stretch I'm demonstrating today is one of my favorite hip openers to use prior to squatting. It's a stretch I learned years ago from Kelly Starrett of @thereadystate. Keys for proper execution: keep your trail leg straight & lean from the hips (don't drop your chest as you lean forward). As always, test - retest to see if this mobility exercise is right for you! Sit into a deep squat. Notice how you feel. Then perform this stretch - and immediately sit into your squat after. If you felt like you could sit more comfortably in the deep squat position - this stretch was efficient for your body to help you get into better positions! 
.
To learn more of my other favorite hip mobility exercises, check out my YouTube video “Hip Mobility for a Perfect Squat.”📲
.
Shout out to @epiersonproductions for the awesome videographer skills in making this video🙏🏼

Today I want to show you why finding your individual movement diagnosis for shoulder pain is so important. Jerome came to me with shoulder pain when snatching - now traditional medial model will try to look at a scan of your shoulder and determine what they see as “abnormal” to be the exact cause of pain. In Jerome’s case they found a small tear in his labrum. However, abnormal findings on MRI do not always equal the exact cause of prin. In fact there is a lot of science to show people have these abnormal findings without any pain. One in particular showed close to 80% of major league pitchers had a labrum abnormality without pain! 
.
So what do we do when an athlete presents with pain? We don’t just try random exercises we see on social media – as there is no “one size fits all” approach for fixing injury. What we do is evaluate and assess to uncover the exact path to take.
.
If you’re dealing with shoulder issues & want to try some of the tests I use to figure out what to do next, start with my blog “How to screen your shoulder pain” on squatuniversity.com📲

Dan @drettenmaier came to me with knee pain that had been frustrating him for the past 5 years! In this video you’ll see his evaluation, part of his treatment & see how he’s doing today!
.
Takeaway: there is no one size fits all method to fixing knee pain. You must evaluate (especially looking at the area above & below the site of pain) and create an individualized plan to address what you find while slowly rebuilding capacity. Remember, a knees over toes position is nothing to fear! However we must understand context and sometimes need to take a step back in order to eventually move forward.
.
Shout out to Dan for putting in the wok to fix this injury & to @3d4medical with the Complete Anatomy app visual of the body in today’s post.

If you don't have symmetrical engagement in your hips you'll often see twists or shifts when lifting.📝

The traditional medical model will try to look at a scan of your back and determine what they see as “abnormal” to be the exact cause of pain. However, there is a ton of research that shows just because you find a problem on MRI does not mean it’s the exact cause of pain. 
.
So what do we do?  We fit your symptoms into a movement diagnosis category! This is something I learned from renowned back expert @backfitpro. A movement diagnosis tells you what motions, postures and loads to avoid in the short term so we don’t continue your pain. It doesn’t matter how many corrective exercises or stability drills you do, if you continue to push into your trigger for pain, it usually won’t get better on it’s own. 
.
The process of limiting individual movement triggers has been shown in research to help reduce pain effectively. It’s not creating fear of movement but rather empowering you to understand your injury so you can take control of the rehab process. 
.
Shout out to @krispy_kremez for being my patient model in this video!

This is a novel exercise to help enhance shoulder stability when lifting overhead - something I first learned from @benlustigphysiotherapy. I’ve used it many times in the past half year with patients of mine recovering from shoulder pain who need more stability when lifting overhead and have seen tremendous improvements. 
.
When to use: be sure to try the test I showed in this video first!!!! If you’re weak - then try & retest to see if this is helpful for you. Remember, “corrective exercises” are only helpful if used in the right situation. Never do an exercise just because it looks cool on social media.😉

Here’s an analysis of one of my recent lifts under the guidance of 2x Olympian @olychad (even coaches need a coach😉). 
.
Off the start things look ok to the knee, but my elbows start to bend too early & then straighten back out as I go into extension (a little more arch back than I’d like to see as well). I dropped to 90 kilos and really focused on keeping my elbows locked through extension with a drop set before going back up. If we reanalyze the second attempt in slow motion you can see my elbows are much straighter through the pull and my extension is even more vertical compared to the first lift. 
.
Is it a perfect lift? Not at all. I still jumped forward slightly and my knee control on the ascent wasn’t as optimal as I would like. But, it’s about progression. Understand what needs to be worked on and have a plan set in place to prioritize and fix faults.

The stretch I'm demonstrating today is one of my favorite hip openers to use prior to squatting. It's a stretch I learned years ago from Kelly Starrett of @thereadystate. Keys for proper execution: keep your trail leg straight & lean from the hips (don't drop your chest as you lean forward). As always, test - retest to see if this mobility exercise is right for you! Sit into a deep squat. Notice how you feel. Then perform this stretch - and immediately sit into your squat after. If you felt like you could sit more comfortably in the deep squat position - this stretch was efficient for your body to help you get into better positions! 
.
To learn more of my other favorite hip mobility exercises, check out my YouTube video “Hip Mobility for a Perfect Squat.”📲
.

One of the most simple technique fixes isn’t always a corrective exercise but rather slowing the movement down & working to “own the lift.” For example, take the squat advice of @eddycoan and perform a 10 second descent squat. If you feel yourself shifting to one side or the other or falling off balance, pause & center yourself before continuing on. For deadlift problems, take the advice of @martinslicis & perform slow tempo lifts especially on the eccentric lower!!! For Olympic lifters, take the advice of @olychad and perform pauses at the knee on your pulls to reinforce the optimal position before extending with the bar. Slowing down tempo & adding pauses can allow you to become more aware of your body. Once aware you can optimize your positioning & enhance you performance when you then decide to go faster. 
.

Today I want to show you why finding your individual movement diagnosis for shoulder pain is so important. Jerome came to me with shoulder pain when snatching - now traditional medial model will try to look at a scan of your shoulder and determine what they see as “abnormal” to be the exact cause of pain. In Jerome’s case they found a small tear in his labrum. However, abnormal findings on MRI do not always equal the exact cause of prin. In fact there is a lot of science to show people have these abnormal findings without any pain. One in particular showed close to 80% of major league pitchers had a labrum abnormality without pain! 
.
So what do we do when an athlete presents with pain? We don’t just try random exercises we see on social media – as there is no “one size fits all” approach for fixing injury. What we do is evaluate and assess to uncover the exact path to take.
.
If you’re dealing with shoulder issues & want to try some of the tests I use to figure out what to do next, start with my blog “How to screen your shoulder pain” on squatuniversity.com📲

node.text:
A while back I got the opportunity to sit down & talk with a mentor of mine Gray Cook of @functionalmvmt (author of the book Movement & co-inventor of the FMS). He talked about how the squatting position in this picture used to be a shooting position the army would teach. However it has fallen out of use as it has become too difficult for many to achieve.
.
Years ago when we talked about the squat the following question wasn’t, “how much do you squat?” The squat used to be a MOVEMENT ever before it was an exercise. Everyone from an 8 year old boy to a 85 year old grandparent) could comfortably get into a deep squat. Things are different today. Most think of squatting ONLY as an exercise & never attempt the movement outside of the gym. We have confused ourselves into thinking because we can squat tremendous weight we are automatically moving well & have command of this basic movement pattern. 
.
It’s time we get back to our roots. Take time each day to sit into this deep squat position. If it’s difficult to get this low at first, give yourself some assistance with a raised heel lift, weightlifting shoe or by holding onto something (like a goblet squat). Then over time, slowly take away this assistance. It is possible but it will take patience and persistence. You’ll be amazed how good you feel when you have the ability to comfortably sit into a deep bodyweight squat for minutes on end.

Is your shoe wide enough? For MOST people the answer is no if you’re wearing nikes, adidas or most other major shoe brands. Shoes that have a narrow toe box smash your toes together & hinder optimal foot function when you lift (meaning it’s WAY harder to keep your foot stable!). 
.
A wide toe box allows your toes to spread out & your foot to function as it was designed. This means more efficient lifting technique!
.
TRY THE SHOE LINER TEST (something I first learned from Dr. Ray McClanahan of @correcttoes) and see what your foot moves like with all of your toes within the edges of the liner.
.
Want to learn more about shoes? Check out my YouTube video “Why you need to wear barefoot shoes.”📲
.
Need some shoe recommendations that are wide enough? Check out @bearfootshoes, @vivobarefoot, @xeroshoes, @altrarunning, @lemsshoes & @feelgrounds to start!

Agree or disagree?🤔
.
My thoughts: the purpose of the box squat is to break up the eccentric lower & concentric ascent. The pause on the box takes out the recoil that occurs with a quick turnaround in the bottom of the squat making it much harder to stand up - and that’s the point. In starting from a dead stop on the ascent the athlete has to work to generate tremendous strength. For certain athletes the box squat can be a very helpful variation in their strength training journey - it just needs to be performed in the right manner to elicit the adaptions it’s designed to produce. 
.
If you’re wanting to learn more about box squats, check out my YouTube video “How to Box Squat feat. Donnie Thompson” @thompsonbowtie (the first powerlifter to total 3000 lbs in competition.
